Partition-level operations.

Three RDD methods operate at the partition level rather than the record level.

Map partitions takes a function that receives an iterator over one partition's records and returns an iterator. Use it when per-record setup is wasteful — opening a database connection, loading a model, or calling an external ay-pee-eye in batches. With map partitions, you do that setup once per partition instead of once per row.

Repartition does a full shuffle to exactly the number of partitions you ask for. Use it to increase parallelism or to rebalance skewed data. Coalesce, by contrast, merges down to fewer partitions without a full shuffle. It is only safe when reducing the partition count — cheap, but it cannot rebalance.

The rule of thumb: when shrinking, use coalesce; when growing or rebalancing, use repartition.

In code, picture three quick checks on the same transactions RDD. First, ask each partition how many records it holds, using map partitions. Second, check the partition count after a repartition to eight — the answer is eight. Third, check the partition count after a coalesce to two — the answer is two.
